[DhtmlXQ_comment0]op ldz c2 37 cc7fh vs sch 2prc 01||第37局中炮七路马对屏风马双炮过河 ||Jim: Well, here you have it, the only file in the GM's book discussing this very volatile opening. And the GM is one of the experts on this opening.||I have uploaded a series of files discussing this opening under the ECCO C04 section. Please go to the menu bar on the left and click on the respective ECCO variation.[/DhtmlXQ_comment0]
[DhtmlXQ_comment11]Red has two other alternatives.||Please click on the variations to view them.[/DhtmlXQ_comment11]
[DhtmlXQ_comment12]As can be seen from the diagram, this is the famous (or rather infamous) opening: Red's central cannon with 7th filed horse vs Black's Screen Horse defense with double pawn ranked cannon variations. ||Black's opening began with C2+4 (right pawn ranked  cannon) and was already very very popular throughout China back in the 1920's. From there, many exciting variations evolved but not many could stood the test of time. However, those that survived evloved further, with new variations and modifications replacing old ones. This could be said to represent the progress of mankind's thought.||This variation has still much room for development and awaits the bold to furhter enrich it.[/DhtmlXQ_comment12]
[DhtmlXQ_comment13]R9+1 is the main counter that red would normally use.||There are two other choices.||Please click in the variation to see them!　[/DhtmlXQ_comment13]
[DhtmlXQ_comment16]This is the modern day way of playing this variation for black. ||Black's cannon forces red to move E7+9 before using the chariot to aim at the left red cannon. This move has effectively replaced older ways of playing this opening like E3+5 as red could play R9=4/R9=6.||It must be mentioned that black's E3+5 followed by  red's R9=6/R9=4 was very fashionable for over 2 decades before black came up with this move.　[/DhtmlXQ_comment16]
[DhtmlXQ_comment17]R9=4 was once tried before...[/DhtmlXQ_comment17]
