[DhtmlXQ_comment19]R6+5 would result in red surrendering the control of the game to black.[/DhtmlXQ_comment19]
[DhtmlXQ_comment20]And black advances the cannon for a skewer.||This move effectively pushes the game into an even more complex situation.　[/DhtmlXQ_comment20]
[DhtmlXQ_comment26]Correct move to play. H7+5 now would be met by red's C8+4 and red would win instead![/DhtmlXQ_comment26]
[DhtmlXQ_comment29]C5+3 now would give the game to black.[/DhtmlXQ_comment29]
[DhtmlXQ_comment39]Red would be killed if he got greedy and played R6=4 to take the horse now![/DhtmlXQ_comment39]
[DhtmlXQ_comment40]And black has seized control of the game from red.||In summary,||the double pawn ranked cannon variation of the screen horses is a very very volatile and complex variation. Be it red or black, the room for error is minimal and a slight mistake would end the game.||Red would have a hard time trying to maintain the lead in the game, and that is why in recent years, red would prefer not to play this variation and this opening has declined.||However, there are still examples of bold and creative inprovisions to this opening in the recent years.||The first man to have eaten crabmeat must have marveled at this delicacy. But those who followed suit and boldy pressed on would also deserve our respect!　[/DhtmlXQ_comment40]
